<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Presidential Council Discusses New Currency </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Presidential Council Discusses New Currency </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0306162294 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1500 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0306162294 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A session of the Presidential Council of Defense and 
National Security was held in the presidential palace today 
under the chairmanship of President Franjo Tudjman. The Council 
discussed the economic and other prerequisites for making the 
kuna a hard currency, the presidential office announced today. 
  Prime Minister Nikica Valentic told the Council that the 
monetary reform in Croatia has been wound up by the introduction 
of a new Croatian currency whose international code is HRK 191. 
The stable and convertible kuna is a prerequisite for the 
further development of the Croatian economy. 
  Valentic stressed that the government will continue to 
implement the stabilization program and to reform the Croatian 
economy. A significant production increase has been registered 
for the first time since 1987. The government will insist on 
financial discipline in payment transactions. Croatia has met 
all IMF conditions by implementing its economic program and is 
expected to sign a letter of intent with the IMF and conclude 
financial agreements with leading international financial 
institutions in the next few months. 
  The Council commended the government, Prime Minister Nikica 
Valentic, and Pero Jurkovic, governor of the National Bank of 
Croatia, for their efforts toward the introduction of the kuna 
and creating conditions for overall international financial 
support and development and for Croatia's economic renewal. The 
Council also discussed some foreign policy issues and Croatia's 
international position. The Council was informed about the 
construction of the Altar of the Homeland, a monument erected on 
Mount Medvednica overlooking Zagreb in memory of heroes who fell 
for Croatia's freedom, the Croatian president's office has 
announced. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

