<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Walesa Confident of Victory in Next Election </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Walesa Confident of Victory in Next Election </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0406184594 Warsaw TVP Television First Program Network in 
Polish 1730 GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0406184594 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw TVP Television First Program Network </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Relayed by TV Polonia Network; passages within quotation </F>
marks recorded] 
  [Text] Before his departure for Great Britain today, 
President Lech Walesa said that he sees an opportunity for the 
reconstruction of a political camp that would attain an 
electoral success similar to that of Solidarity five years ago. 
The condition for this is, however, that Solidarity politicians 
start to listen to him. Walesa stated that he is certain of his 
victory in the presidential election next year. 
  [Correspondent Maciej Sojka] Walesa feels that low ratings 
in 
public opinion poll surveys--in which he is led by several other 
candidates for the presidential chair--do not negate his chances 
of a second term in the Belweder Palace. 
  [Walesa] "That is why I am convinced I will win as 
president." 
  [Sojka] The president does not yet know whether he will sign 
the neo-popiwek law. He admitted that he sees no reason to 
hurry with this decision. 
  [Walesa] "Well, not much is taking place. I see certain 
people who have decent earnings, of 90 million, and these 
paupers who have a million--and we are so scared of them?" 
  [Sojka] Asked whether he will stand by his invitation to 
German President Roman Herzog to the commemorations of the 50th 
anniversary of the Warsaw Uprising, the president said that he 
never goes back on his word. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

