<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   RSK Official on Talks, Italian Alliance </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    RSK Official on Talks, Italian Alliance </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206165394 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1341 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0206165394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Obrenovac, 2 Jun -- Borislav Mikelic, prime minister 
of the government of the republic of Serb Krajina [RSK], today 
denied reports that representatives of the RSK and Croatia were 
going to resume talks in Athens, Greece. "We have not yet fixed 
a location and date for further negotiations between Knin and 
Zagreb. I am not sure how some news organizations have come up 
with reports that this is going to take place in Athens," 
Mikelic told Obrenovac Radio. 
  "Our attitude is known anyway; anywhere except in Germany or 
within Croatia's borders," Mikelic added. He stressed that he 
was waiting for the next meeting with cochairmen Owen and 
Stoltenberg which will probably take place next week in Geneva. 
"Only when we have presented our arguments and heard their 
opinion will we decide where to hold further negotiations," 
Mikelic said. 
  The RSK prime minister said that the dispute over where to 
hold talks "increasingly resembles a match that is under way." 
[as received] He accuses the three EU ambassadors who released a 
six-point statement in Knin in early May, thereby prejudicing a 
political solution, of stalling the negotiations. Asked by the 
Obrenovac Radio presenter about a possible alliance between 
Italy and the RSK, Mikelic said that he would soon meet Italian 
Prime Minister Berlusconi and that he saw no reason why Krajina 
should not cooperate with one of Europe's economic powers. 
  "At the moment Croatia should pay more attention to Dalmatia 
and Istria than to us. First, we are another country. Second, 
they should save whatever can be saved. Certainly, the Kuna 
will not save them but let Europe witness where Croatia has 
ended up under the leadership of the Croatian Democratic Union," 
Mikelic told Obrenovac Radio. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

