<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Izetbegovic, U.S. Senators Discuss Arms Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Izetbegovic, U.S. Senators Discuss Arms Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0506154894 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1500 GMT 5 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0506154894 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bosnia-Herzegovina Presidency President Alija 
Izetbegovic had talks today with a delegation of the U.S. 
Congress made up of senators Robert Dole, Joseph Biden, and John 
Warner. 
  Izetbegovic spoke about the problem of lifting the arms 
embargo imposed on the legitimate Bosnia-Herzegovina Government. 
Being aware of the fact that it is really unlikely to expect 
the embargo to be lifted, Izetbegovic proposed to the U.S. 
senators that, instead of supplying the Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Government with arms, the Serb heavy weapons should be seized; 
this would represent the implementation of UN Security Council 
Resolution 752. 
  Senator Dole stressed that the condition for the United 
States to send its troops to Bosnia is attainment of a 
comprehensive peace solution. Dole also said that a fair peace 
in Bosnia must be restored, and therefore in his mind it is 
wrong to speak about the percentages of territory as the primary 
issue rather than about the principles of that peace. 
  The U.S. senators brought to Sarajevo 750 kg of clothes, 
3,000 pairs of children's shoes, and a larger quantity of toys, 
books, and medicines. The U.S. delegation has left Sarajevo for 
Normandy where it is to take part in the D-Day celebrations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-31168 </DOCNO>
