<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Butrus-Ghali Confers With Officials </H4>

<F P=102> LD0606141494 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1339 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0606141494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, June 6 (TANJUG) -- U.N. Secretary-General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali, who arrived in Geneva late on Sunday, early 
on Monday conferred with his special envoy to former Yugoslavia 
Yasushi Akashi and Co-Chairman of the Conference on the Former 
Yugoslavia Thorvald Stoltenberg, it was said in the U.N. 
headquarters in Geneva. Akashi gave Butrus-Ghali a detailed 
account of the efforts made over the past four days in order to 
enable the beginning of a conference on a comprehensive 
cessation of hostilities in Bosnia-Herzegovina, said a spokesman 
at the U.N. headquarters in Geneva. 
  Butrus-Ghali was pleased with the fact that Akashi's efforts 
were fruitful and expressed hope that this would pave the way to 
a comprehensive political settlement in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Speaking on behalf of the mediators and the two negotiating 
sides (the Bosnian Serb republic and the Moslem-Croat 
federation), the spokesman has officially confirmed that the 
talks began at 11.15 A.M. (0915 GMT) on Monday with a meeting 
between Akashi and Vice- President of the Moslem-Croat 
Federation Ejup Ganic. 
  Butrus-Ghali especially thanked Akashi for providing a 
platform for the beginning of the talks and promised to give him 
his full support in the forthcoming negotiating process. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

