<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Karadzic Wants `Permanent' Cease-Fire </H4>

<F P=102> LD0606153794 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1422 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0606153794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, 6 Jun (TANJUG) -- Srpska republic president 
Radovan Karadzic has said that he is ready to sign a document on 
a permanent cessation of hostilities throughout the territory of 
the former Yugoslav Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina. Karadzic 
stressed that the Serb side is in favor of a permanent, not 
limited, cessation of all forms of hostilities. 
  Early this morning, at a meeting between Yasushi Akashi, the 
UN special envoy for the former Yugoslavia, and Muslim Vice 
President Ejup Ganic [title as received], the Muslim-Croat side 
insisted that it would accept only two months of a cessation of 
hostilities at the most. The Muslims and Croats believe that in 
that period an agreement on the basis of the contact group's 
proposal for the territorial division of the former Yugoslav 
Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina should be reached. 
  Ganic told Akashi that "the Muslim-Croat side does not, 
under 
any circumstances, want the Geneva conference to freeze the 
current situation in former Bosnia-Herzegovina." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

