Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Bosnian Presidency Statement </H4>

<F P=102> AU0606191194 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1700 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0606191194 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The cabinet of our country's president of the 
Presidency has released a statement explaining the position of 
the Federation and Republic state delegation at the negotiations. 
  The delegation demands that the cease-fire throughout the 
territory of Bosnia-Herzegovina should be for a period of four 
weeks. Arms of 12.7-mm caliber and upwards must be concentrated 
far from the front lines, and have to be guarded and monitored 
by the UN Protection Forces [UNPROFOR] and NATO. The monitoring 
of the cease-fire and communication between the opponents would 
be secured by UNPROFOR according to the procedure coordinated 
with the legitimate authorities in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The Bosnia-Herzegovina delegation also insists on guarantees 
for the unimpaired passage of humanitarian organizations 
throughout Bosnia-Herzegovina, the immediate release of all 
civilians held by the aggressor side, the unconditional and 
immediate opening of Tuzla airport for the delivery of goods for 
civilian purposes, the cessation of ethnic cleansing, and the 
effective implementation of all Security Council resolutions 
regarding the protection of security zones. 
  The negotiations in Geneva are not being conducted directly 
with the representatives of the aggressor, but according to the 
principle of separate rooms. UN representatives are acting as 
mediators for the proposals of the parties involved, reads the 
statement from the cabinet of the president of the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Presidency. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

