<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    UN Insists on Four-Month Cease-Fire </H4>

<F P=102> AU0706123394 Paris AFP in English 0932 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0706123394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Geneva, June 7 (AFP) -- UN special envoy 
Yasushi Akashi said Tuesday that he would insist that Bosnia's 
warring parties accept a four-month countrywide ceasefire at 
peace talks that entered their second day here. Akashi, asked 
if he would be prepared to reduce the duration of the ceasefire 
as demanded by the Moslem-led Bosnian government and their Croat 
allies, answered firmly: "No, I am not." But, he added "our 
negotiation with both parties separately is proceeding 
exceedingly well. The atmosphere is businesslike, frank and 
friendly." 
  The duration of the ceasefire is one of the principle 
sticking-points in the ceasefire talks which began here Monday 
between Bosnia's Croats, Moslems and Serbs, UN diplomats said. 
[passage omitted] 
  Akashi said that although the ceasefire talks were "separate 
from a political settlement ... of course the two agreements 
have to be closely linked." Akashi said there were still "a few 
difficult questions which have to be resolved." But, he added 
"we will make every effort possible to anchor the agreement by 
tonight." [passage omitted] 
  Akashi was due to meet the Serb delegation led by Radovan 
Karadzic Tuesday morning for an hour before joining a meeting 
between UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali and the joint 
heads of the Bosnian delegation, Kresimir Zubak and Ejup Ganic, 
around 11:30 a.m. (0930 GMT). "Then we will see the Bosnian 
side and the Serb side and we will repeat this throughout the 
day," Akashi said. 
  The UN envoy said he did not envisage the Bosnian and 
Bosnian 
Serb delegations would sit at the same negotiating table except 
"for the signature" of an agreement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

