<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tinca, Leotard Hold Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tinca, Leotard Hold Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0206200994 Bucharest Radio Romania Network in Romanian 
1900 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0206200994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest Radio Romania Network </F>
<F P=105>  Romanian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In talks today delegations from the Romanian and 
French Defense Ministries reviewed the current stage in 
bilateral relations and their perspectives and assessed the 
current situation in Europe and the tendencies of security 
structures at the continental level. 
  Romanian National Defense Minister Gheorghe Tinca told us 
that he had asked French Minister Leotard to urge the important 
French companies to come to Romania to cooperate both in the 
field of military equipment and in the civilian economy. 
  Similarly they assessed cooperation between Romania and 
France, as well as between the two armed forces, within the 
framework of NATO, in the context of the Partnership for Peace 
initiative, and within the Western European Union [WEU], where 
they noted Romania's status as an associate partner within that 
organization, a status granted to central European countries. 
  The talks also focused on the perspectives of strengthening 
European stability, the readiness of the two parties to 
cooperate in that domain, and the possibilities opened by the 
stability pact initiated by French Prime Minister Edouard 
Balladur. 
  The talks held this afternoon by the Romanian and French 
defense delegations proved to be a good opportunity to reconfirm 
the friendly relations between Romania and France and the two 
armed forces and the mutual desire to further those relations, 
in view of the need for cooperation to find the most favorable 
solutions to remodel the security context and common future of 
united Europe. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

