<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Silajdzic Returns From Geneva; Comments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Silajdzic Returns From Geneva; Comments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606233194 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
2200 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0606233194 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bosnia-Herzegovina Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic 
returned from Geneva to Sarajevo this evening. He stated that 
the international mediators have been trying to impose a 
take-it-or-leave-it solution by exerting pressure on 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, stressing that the contact group said it 
would put forward its proposal in a week or two. We are not 
pleased with the proposal of the territorial division in eastern 
Bosnia, and there are no instruments of coercion. Therefore, we 
are wondering how any kind of agreement would be implemented, 
Silajdzic added. He also said that Bosnia-Herzegovina demanded 
that NATO offer guarantees for the implementation of the 
agreement and secure Bosnia-Herzegovina's borders in case the 
peace agreement is accepted. Bosnia-Herzegovina also demands 
specific plans for the return of refugees and clear guarantees 
that reconstruction aid will be provided. Silajdzic announced 
that members of the contact group would visit Sarajevo in 
approximately 10 days to resume negotiations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

