<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnian Croat Shelling of Brcko Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnian Croat Shelling of Brcko Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606214594 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2117 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0606214594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Brcko, June 6 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Croats on Monday 
evening shelled from multiple rocket launchers civilian targets 
in the Serb town of Brcko in the north, TANJUG's correspondent 
reports. 
  An all-out alert has been sounded in the town. 
  According to incomplete reports, the attack was launched 
from 
the Croat positions at Vucilovci around Orasje, some seven 
kilometres northwest of Brcko. There are no reports on 
casualties, but material damage is extensive. This was the 
seventh artillery attack on Brcko in the past four weeks, and 
the fourth launched from Bosnian Croat positions. In all four 
attacks, the Croats used 128-mm shells. The Moslems mostly use 
tank shells. The first six attacks left seven people dead and 
40 wounded, including several children. 
  U.N. observers, who have been deployed in Brcko since May 7, 
have conducted their own investigations into all the attacks on 
Brcko, which is situated at the neck of the vital corridor 
linking the eastern and western parts of the Bosnian Serb 
Republic. 
  The Serbs on May 7 proclaimed a unilateral truce in the 
Brcko 
area and reached agreement with U.N. peacekeepers on the 
deployment of U.N. observers in the town. Early in May, the 
local Croat commander in Orasje announced an all-out attack on 
Brcko by the combined Croat-Moslem force whose only aim, he 
said, was to cut the Serb corridor along the Sava River. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-31220 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu109_i_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-109 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

