<H3> <TI>   Refugees Returning From Libya Face `Complications' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Refugees Returning From Libya Face `Complications' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0606162694 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0606162694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Complications have developed regarding the return 
from Libya of some 900 children, 150 counselors, (?doctors), and 
other accompanying staff, who, one year ago, [words indistinct]. 
The council [word indistinct] educated in Libya and established 
in Zenica, recently sent a delegation to Sarajevo to consult 
with the Bosnia-Herzegovina Government and secure as quick a 
return home as possible. 
  After talks in the Foreign Ministry, parents were informed 
that the Libyan authorities are insisting on flying the children 
and their counselors from Libya to Split. That is why it is 
necessary to secure the permission of the UN High Commissioner 
for Refugees for several flights, since the international 
community has imposed an economic embargo on Libya. The Libyan 
[words indistinct] are offering their planes or [words 
indistinct]. However, such an endeavor actually means violating 
the embargo. The parents' delegation from Zenica has expressed 
doubt regarding the swift resolution of this problem, and is 
calling on the Bosnia-Herzegovina Government to engage [words 
indistinct] as well as observing the date agreed upon for the 
return [words indistinct]. 

</TEXT>

