<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    `Freezing' of Current Situation Feared </H4>

<F P=102> LD0606120394 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1100 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0606120394 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] After the talks between the joint Croat-Bosniak 
delegation and Yasushi Akashi and his aides, Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Federation President Zubak said: We have completed the first 
round of talks, during which we presented to Mr. Akashi our 
proposal for an agreement which would mean the cessation of 
hostilities in Bosnia-Herzegovina. The essence of our proposals 
is that the deadlines and modalities of establishing a 
cease-fire should not lead to the freezing of the current 
situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina, President Zubak said. 
  Federation Vice President Ganic added that he expects a new 
round of talks at 1700, not with [Bosnian Serb leader] Karadzic 
but with Akashi and his team of military experts who are 
supported by cochairman Stoltenberg and a UN team. 
  Secretary-General Butrus-Ghali and his special envoy Akashi 
had a meeting in the Palais des Nations this afternoon. They 
discussed the modalities and deadlines for a cease-fire in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. The United Nations is hoping that the 
cease-fire negotiations will begin today. 

</TEXT>

