<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Olechowski on Russian Achievements, Problems </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Olechowski on Russian Achievements, Problems </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606153694 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 1200 
GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0606153694 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Poland does not want to turn its back on the east 
and wants to maintain good relations with all of the countries 
that have emerged since the demise of the Soviet Union, Foreign 
Minister Andrzej Olechowski said at the opening of a two-day 
conference on Poland's eastern policy in Warsaw. Minister 
Olechowski emphasized that the building of democratic structures 
in the east is a lot more difficult and that delays in the 
process are inevitable. 
  When asked by journalists whether certain developments in 
the 
situation in Russia could constitute a danger to Poland, 
Minister Olechowski replied: 
  [begin Olechowski recording] From that direction--often say 
this--neo-imperialism, if it was stepped up; we do not 
overdramatize this in any way [sentence as heard]. We can also 
see very positive signals coming from that direction. One 
should mention, for example, Russia's role in the recent 
Ukrainian conflict or the role played in the internal Ukrainian 
difficulties. One could mention the Latvian-Lithuanian Treaty. 
We are awaiting a similar treaty for Estonia. It will be an 
important litmus test for us. 
  Chaos and further economic disintegration are certainly bad 
for us. If the situation were to deteriorate even further, it 
would obviously make our lives very difficult. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

