<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Karadzic, Krajisnik Comment on Talks </H4>

<F P=102> LD0706125194 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1209 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0706125194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, 7 Jun (TANJUG) -- Srpska republic president 
Radovan Karadzic says that there is a possibility of a document 
marking the end of the war being signed this afternoon in 
Geneva's Palais des Nations. Following his talks with Yasushi 
Akashi, UN special envoy for the former Yugoslavia, Karadzic 
said at a news conference: "We have conducted difficult but 
constructive talks. Our suggestion about a general 12-month 
cease-fire was not accepted." 
  Momcilo Krajisnik, president of the Srpska republic 
assembly, 
said to a TANJUG correspondent: 
  "We expect that a document will be signed on an 
all-encompassing four-month cease-fire, but we still have to 
wait for the Muslim side's reply. Yasushi Akashi is expected to 
meet the Muslim delegation this afternoon. Afterwards, a 
plenary session may take place and, eventually, documents may be 
signed. Everything is still uncertain, though." 

</TEXT>

