<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Akashi Starts New Round of Talks </H4>

<F P=102> LD0706214394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1947 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0706214394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Geneva, June 7 (TANJUG) -- Special U.N. envoy for 
former Yugoslavia Yasushi Akashi on Tuesday evening started a 
new round of bilateral talks with Bosnia's warring parties after 
which he would decide whether or not to continue the Geneva 
conference on the cessation of hostilities in that war-torn 
former Yugoslav republic. 
  Visibly exhausted by futile attempts over the past five days 
to establish communication between the belligerents and create 
conditions for talks, Akashi said on Tuesday afternoon the 
conference might be continued in Sarajevo and in Pale. 
  The international mediator is currently meeting for the 
third 
time in a single day with vice-president of the Moslem-Croat 
Federation Ejup Gapic to persuade him to accept a platform on a 
four-month general ceasefire proposed by the contact group on 
Bosnia. 
  The Bosnian Serb delegation has indicated it may accept the 
platform, and Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic has stated 
that an agreement to that effect may be reached by the evening. 
  The start of the talks was delayed for four days because the 
Moslems claimed all armed Serbs had not left the three-kilometre 
exclusion zone around Gorazde in eastern Bosnia as set out in 
U.N. Security Council Resolution 913. 
  The Moslems on Monday attempted to seize the territory 
around 
Gorazde from which the Serbs had withdrawn, a U.N. spokesman in 
Sarajevo said on Tuesday. 
  The plenary session of the Bosnia peace talks has had to be 
postponed for three times because the Moslem-Croat delegation 
remains firm in its position that a ceasefire can be signed for 
a maximum of four to six weeks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

