<H3> <TI>   Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Karadzic: Muslims Want War, Not Peace </H4>

<F P=102> LD0706215694 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 2040 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0706215694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Geneva, 7 Jun (TANJUG) -- Late this evening 
Srpska republic president Radovan Karadzic said after yet 
another round of talks with special envoy Yasushi Akashi that 
the Muslim side wanted war and not peace. "It is also obvious 
that someone is supporting them from the outside," he pointed 
out. 
  Before leaving the UN headquarters, Karadzic said that the 
Serb delegation would remain in Geneva until tomorrow to see if 
the Muslim-Croat delegation would soften its stand according to 
which it would accept only a four-week cease-fire. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

