<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Talks `Undermined' by Muslim-Croat Side </H4>

<F P=102> LD0806022494 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2123 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806022494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Geneva, June 7 (TANJUG)--Ejup Ganic, vice-president 
of the Bosnian Moslem-Croat Federation, retained his inflexible 
position after a third round of talks with special U.N. Envoy 
Yasushi Akashi in Geneva on Tuesday evening that the Federation 
could only accept a four-week-long ceasefire for war-torn 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. Proceeding from a declaration adopted by 
the contact group on Bosnia on May 13 in Geneva, Akashi has been 
insisting on a four-month truce. 
  In Ganic's view, everything else but a four-week ceasefire 
would imply retaining the status quo from which only the Serbs 
would benefit. He also reprimanded reporters at the Palais des 
Nations for ignoring his accusations of the Serbs. 
  "I have seen all the papers and my statements are nowhere to 
be found. 
  "Today I told (U.N. Secretary-General Butrus) Butrus-Ghali 
he 
is chiefly to blame for the spreading of the ethnic cleansing 
policy in the world," said Ganic aggressively. 
  Regardless of his fervent anti-Serb campaign, Ganic is no 
longer able to hide from the reporters the simple truth that the 
conference is being undermined by the Moslem-Croat side. 
  Early in the afternoon, Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic 
said the Serbs were prepared to accept Akashi's suggestion for a 
four-month ceasefire and that some results conducive to peace 
would be achieved in Geneva after all. More bilateral talks 
will be held in the evening. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

