<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnia Peace Talks Continue in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Akashi: Serbs Accept 4-Month Cease-Fire </H4>

<F P=102> LD0706223094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2128 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0706223094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, June 7 (TANJUG) -- Special United Nations 
(U.N.) envoy for former Yugoslavia [words indistinct] said at 
the U.N. headquarters in Geneva late on Tuesday evening that the 
talks on a ceasefire in Bosnia-Herzegovina would continue 
tomorrow, despite great difficulties. Akashi also announced 
meetings with the Moslem-Croat delegation and with Bosnian Serb 
President Radovan Karadzic on Wednesday. This means that a 
plenary session will again not be held on Wednesday, in all 
probability. 
  Akashi confirmed to reporters that Bosnian Serbs had 
accepted 
a four-month ceasefire as proposed in a declaration adopted by 
the contact group for Bosnia-Herzegovina in Geneva on May 13. 
The latest Moslem proposal for a ceasefire is four weeks plus 
four weeks, Akashi said, but did not elaborate on the stand of 
the U.N., which is the mediator in the peace talks, regarding 
these proposals. 

</TEXT>

