<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Slovak Minority Leader on Absence of Rights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Slovak Minority Leader on Absence of Rights </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0706121394 Bratislava SLOVENSKA REPUBLIKA in Slovak 3 Jun 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> AU0706121394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava SLOVENSKA REPUBLIKA </F>
<F P=105>  Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [TA SR report: "No Guarantee of Rights; On the Position of </F>
the Slovak Minority in Poland"] 
  [Text] Warsaw--An estimated 15,000-20,000 Slovaks live in 
Poland at present. But the number of those who no longer 
identify with their Slovak origin is twice as large. However, 
the Slovak minority in Poland does not represent a problem on 
the scale, for example, of the Hungarian minority in Slovakia. 
"During the reform of the entire state administration, we were 
practically left to our own devices. We do not have any rights 
guaranteed by the Constitution and a law on minorities does not 
exist in Poland," Lubomir Molitoris, secretary of the Central 
Committee of the Cultural and Social Association of Czechs and 
Slovaks in Poland, said about the present position of the Slovak 
minority in Poland. 
  Some protection is somewhat noticeable in the sphere of 
education, where a Ministry of Education decree is in force on 
the principles of minority education and maintaining a national 
identity. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

