<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Krajina Leader on Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Krajina Leader on Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706222094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2205 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0706222094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Knin, June 7 (TANJUG) -- Prime minister of the 
republic of Serb Krajina Borislav Mikelic on Tuesday [7 June] 
assessed as positive the talks with a United States (U.S.) 
non-government delegation and said he was confident that its 
members would leave with quite different opinions about the Serb 
people of Krajina than they had as a result of the anti-Serb 
proganda abroad before their arrival. Mikelic met with the U.S. 
delegation in Krajina's political center of Knin on Tuesday. 
The delegation included many prominent former U.S. ambassadors 
to the United Nations, influential diplomats and representatives 
of the U.S. mass media, headed by the editor-in-chief of Time 
magazine. 
  Mikelic and national security advisor to the Krajina 
president General Mile Novakovic informed the visitors about the 
current political situation in Serb-Croat relations and about 
the genesis of the armed conflicts in the territory of former 
Yugoslavia. The purpose of this visit was to review the 
realization of the ceasefire agreement with Croatia and the 
withdrawal of forces, and the conditions, efficiency and type of 
work done by the members of the United Nations peace force in 
the field. 
  The republic of Serb Krajina was formed in 1991 in 
Serb-populated parts of former Croatia in answer to Croatia's 
secession from former Yugoslavia and attempts to reduce the Serb 
people to a national minority. Since March 1992, Krajina has 
been a U.N.-protected area, which however, did not prevent 
Croatia from attacking the area on four occasions, razing some 
twenty Serb villages and killing more than a thousand civilians. 
  The agreement on a ceasefire and separation of forces, which 
was signed by Krajina and Croatia at the Russian Embassy in 
Zagreb in late March, became effective on April 4. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

