<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Joint Scientific Projects With Albania </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Joint Scientific Projects With Albania </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0706154094 Skopje NOVA MAKEDONIJA in Macedonian 1 Jun 94 p 
3 </F>

<F P=103> AU0706154094 </F>
<F P=104>  Skopje NOVA MAKEDONIJA </F>
<F P=105>  Macedonian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Cooperation Through Joint Scientific </F>
Projects"] 
  [Text] Branko Crvenkovski, prime minister for Macedonia 
[The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FRYOM], yesterday 
received an Albanian Government delegation headed by the 
president of the Committee for Science and Technology, Maxim 
Konomi. 
  The meeting emphasized the satisfaction with the action 
taken 
to promote cooperation between the two countries through the 
Agreement on Scientific and Technological Cooperation that will 
be signed by Macedonian Science Minister Aslan Selmani and 
Konomi. 
  It was concluded that this agreement was very important for 
promoting cooperation in the area of science as a basis for 
cooperation in more important areas of mutual interest for the 
two countries. The possibilities for cooperation envisaged in 
the agreement open the road to bilateral and multilateral 
cooperation between the two states, as well as cooperation among 
the countries in the Balkans, Europe, and the world. Regional 
scientific projects are the main projects for which financing is 
envisaged by the European Union and the United Nations, above 
all traffic, economic, energy, information, and ecology programs. 
  Yesterday, the Albanian delegation also had a meeting with 
the president of the Macedonian Academy of Science and Arts, 
Ksente Bogoev. Interest in cooperation between the two 
academies was expressed, as well as general readiness to 
organize a meeting of the delegations of the academies in Skopje 
and Tirana. Cooperation can be also implemented by organizing a 
scientific symposium on the ecological protection of Lake Ohrid, 
which is of great significance for both countries. 
  Frederika Popovska-Pavlovska, vice president of St. Cyril 
and 
Methodius University and responsible for international 
cooperation, informed the guests from Albania about the 
organization in our universities. She expressed interest in 
cooperation at university level, and also at the level of 
particular faculties and scientific institutions, which will 
enable cooperation on the level of teaching and scientific 
personnel through joint scientific projects. Interest was also 
expressed in including the two countries in the TEMPUS and 
KOPERNIKUS programs, which involve cooperation among higher 
educational institutions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-31294 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu110_d_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-110 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Proposal on Dam `Political,' Unacceptable </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EU Proposal on Dam `Political,' Unacceptable </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706135194 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1000 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0706135194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1000 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Foreign Minister Eduard Kukan by </F>
correspondent Zuzana Stukovska; date and place not 
given--recorded] 
  [Text] [Stukovska] To attain a political compromise, 
European Union [EU] experts have recommended to Slovakia an 
increase in the average inflow into the old Danube River bed at 
the Gabcikovo Dam to 800 cubic meters a second. Is this 
proposal acceptable to the Slovak Government? 
  [Kukan] The EU commission's recommendation to increase the 
inflow in the old Danube River bed to 800 cubic meters a second 
is a proposal for a political solution that is not acceptable to 
the Slovak Government. We think there are a sufficient number 
of other technical measures to attain the aim put forward by 
Hungary; we are also interested in achieving an agreement on 
this. We are presenting these technical proposals and would 
like to discuss them. 
  We would like to explain to the EU that our approach to this 
issue is serious. However, its expert group's recommendation--it 
gave us a number of proposals and all were acceptable to us 
except this one, which seems to us to be a political 
solution--we reject, and we reject any political pressure to 
have it accepted. 
  [Stukovska] Obviously there will be talks with Hungary. At 
which level should they be conducted? 
  [Kukan] We are interested in continuing the talks on 
temporary water management with Hungary. You, however, know the 
current situation in Hungary: A new government is being 
constituted, a new parliament has been elected. We have certain 
positive signs that the Hungarian position might be changing. I 
am a realist and will wait and see what happens. We are having 
continuous diplomatic correspondence with the Hungarian Foreign 
Ministry. To answer your question, These talks will be 
technical talks between experts dealing with the issues linked 
to temporary water management. 
  [Stukovska] Can you tell us, at least approximately, when 
they might be held? 
  [Kukan] It depends on when a new government is formed in 
Hungary. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

