<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Kovac on D-Day Meetings With Leaders </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Kovac on D-Day Meetings With Leaders </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706225494 Bratislava STV 1 Television Network in Slovak 
1730 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0706225494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava STV 1 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Slovak President Michal Kovac returned home this 
evening from Great Britain and France, where he took part in the 
50th anniversary celebrations of the Allied landings in Normandy. 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified correspondent] Mr. 
President, 
the purpose of your visit was, above all, to honor the memory of 
those who fell during the historical event of the Normandy 
invasion. However, how do you assess the importance of this 
visit and your meetings with many important politicians from the 
foreign policy angle? 
  [Kovac] It was an opportunity to establish personal contact 
with a whole range of state representatives, mainly with those I 
had not met until now. [passage omitted] Of course, it was also 
an opportunity to deepen still further those contacts that 
already exist. I have in mind the meeting with President Bill 
Clinton. I had the opportunity to listen to their interest in 
Slovakia. They wanted to know what is happening in Slovakia. 
They expressed an understanding of our policy. They were 
interested to see the continuation of the Slovak transformation, 
of building friendly relations with neighboring states, and they 
want Slovakia to contribute toward the stability of the Central 
European region. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

