<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Denies Trying To `Split' Minority </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Denies Trying To `Split' Minority </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0306185394 Budapest MTI in English 1807 GMT 3 Jun 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0306185394 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, June 3 (MTI) -- The chairman of the 
Democratic Union of Vojvodina Hungarians (VMDK) in Serbia, 
Andras Agoston, recently accused the Hungarian Government -- in 
press statements carried in Hungary -- of having tried to split 
the VMDK. 
  Ministry officials said the Foreign Ministry has always 
accepted the VMDK as the legitimate representative of Hungarians 
in Vojvodina. In this spirit leaders of the Foreign Ministry 
held talks with the VMDK delegations in Hungary, and in the 
course of official and unofficial visits to Yugoslavia. The 
Foreign Ministry and the Hungarian diplomatic corps has done 
much to make the problems of Vojvodina Hungarians known in the 
world, mainly in the international organisations trying to 
settle the South Slav crisis. 
  Hungarian foreign affairs leaders, including Foreign 
Minister 
Geza Jeszenszky, State Secretaries Andras Kelemen and Janos 
Martonyi, firmly supported the VMDK during their visits to 
Yugoslavia in the past years, agreeing to appear at events 
organised by the VMDK, and backing the VMDK publicly. 
  Hungarian foreign affairs leaders continually pressed for 
the 
VMDK to be accepted as a political negotiating side by Yugoslav 
partners, and for negotiating the issues they raised. 
  The Hungarian Foreign Ministry has also provided concrete 
financial support to the activity of the Vox Humana Humanitarian 
Service, set up with encouragement from the VMDK. Alongside the 
VMDK, Hungary helped ease the winter hardship for Vojvodina 
Hungarians, Foreign Ministry officials told MTI. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-31331 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu110__a94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-110-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Spokesman on `Sign Bill' in Slovakia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Spokesman on `Sign Bill' in Slovakia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0706180194 Budapest MTI in English 1339 GMT 7 Jun 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0706180194 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 7 June (MTI) -- The Hungarian Foreign 
Ministry follows with sympathy the efforts of the Slovak 
politicians who take a genuine stand for fulfilling the norms 
accepted at the time of their country's membership in the 
Council of Europe, spokesman for the Hungarian Foreign Ministry 
Janos Herman said today. Herman made the comment at his usual 
Tuesday [7 June] press briefing in answer to a question on how 
Hungary received the fiasco of the so-called "sign bill" in 
Bratislava's parliament. The bill would have made it possible 
to use road and village signs in the Hungarian language. 
  Herman stressed that Budapest is highly appreciative of the 
fact that Slovak Prime Minister Jozef Moravcik indicated his 
government's intention to re-submit the bill on the use of 
Hungarian signs to Parliament as soon as this becomes possible 
under the Slovak constitutional framework. 
  Herman also said the text of the Hungarian-Slovak 
deportation 
agreement has, in effect, been completed, and now only requires 
an agreement on the date for signing it. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

