<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Commander: No Soldiers Outside Borders </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Commander: No Soldiers Outside Borders </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806161794 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1501 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0806161794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 8 Jun (TANJUG) -- Colonel General Momcilo 
Perisic, Yugoslav Army chief of general staff [CGS], held a 
working meeting today with representatives of the Yugoslav media 
in the central Yugoslav Army Club. 
  "I am not asking you to depict the situation in the Yugoslav 
Army as being better than it really is," General Perisic told 
the correspondents. He urged the building of better mutual 
trust through various forms of cooperation. General Perisic 
recalled that not a single member of the Yugoslav Army is 
outside Yugoslav borders, except for diplomatic and consular 
missions of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia abroad. He added 
that the Yugoslav Army is not causing any incidents on the 
border between the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and the Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia. These incidents, he explained, 
come as a consequence of an undefined internationally recognized 
border between the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and the Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia. 
  The Yugoslav Army CGS also stressed that the process of 
depolitization of the Yugoslav Army has been completed, and 
spoke about the Army's high technical and technological level 
which has been maintained despite the sanctions. 

</TEXT>

