<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fuel Company Says Supplies To Improve </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fuel Company Says Supplies To Improve </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0806190394 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0806190394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Vesna Tenjovic] </F>
  [Excerpt] The supply of gasoline will improve, but the 
prices of derivatives will not decrease for the time being, said 
Zivko Soklovacki, director of the Public Liaison Office of the 
Serbian Oil Industry [Naftna Industrija Srbije -- NIS]. Vesna 
Tenjovic reports. 
  [Begin recording] Owing to great pressure, it is diesel that 
is mostly produced at the moment. The production is progressing 
according to plan and it should remain at last year's level. 
Rationalization within the oil industry has led to a decrease in 
expenses, which has created conditions for a 4.5 percent 
decrease in prices. However, owing to problems that arose in 
the earlier period, NIS believes that the price of derivatives 
should not be decreased immediately, but rather after the 
company has been consolidated. A decrease in taxes would also 
create leeway for decreasing prices. NIS is also preparing a 
program of rationalization and reorganization of the company, 
but the changes probably will not be great. [passage omitted] 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

