<F P=101> Kosovo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbian, U.S. Officials Discuss Kosovo Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbian, U.S. Officials Discuss Kosovo Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806143794 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1302 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0806143794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pristina, 8 Jun (TANJUG) -- Kosovo District leader 
Milos Simovic, and provincial information secretary Bosko 
Drobnjak had talks in Pristina today with Jonathan Moore, head 
of the State Department desk for Serbia and Montenegro, about 
the political situation in the province, the position of 
national minorities, and the possibilities for restoring 
dialogue. 
  According to a public statement, Simovic said that the 
political and security situation in the province is better this 
year because more ethnic Albanian citizens have been meeting 
their obligations toward the state. This was clearly influenced 
by official statements by a number of diplomats and 
representatives of the European states who, while visiting 
Kosovo and Metohija, presented their governments' clear stand 
regarding the inviolability of the borders of the Republic of 
Serbia and Yugoslavia. 
  According to the statement, Jonathan Moore stated that his 
country is abiding by the stance which rules out the possibility 
of secession by any one part of the Republic of Serbia and 
Yugoslavia. Milos Simovic stated that even though it has not 
been officially registered as a party with the relevant 
republican ministry, the Democratic Alliance of Kosovo has not 
experienced any obstacles nor pressures in freely performing its 
activities, despite the fact that it has been at the forefront 
of the anti-Serbian campaign. 
  The talks were also attended by Matthew Palmer, a 
representative of the U.S. Embassy in Belgrade. 

</TEXT>

