<F P=100> MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Increasingly High Price' of Sanctions Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Increasingly High Price' of Sanctions Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906110894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1041 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0906110894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Mladen Stancic] </F>
  [Text] Skopje, June 9 (TANJUG) -- Businessmen in The Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia (FYROM) are paying an 
increasingly high price because of the "southern traffic 
pocket", created by the imposition of the U.N. sanctions on 
Yugoslavia and Greece's trade blockade of the FYROM. The 
transport of goods, raw materials and semi-manufactures via the 
roundabout east-west corridor has resulted in a drastic rise of 
business costs and, according to FYROM businessmen, will require 
an additional 40 million U.S. dollars by the end of the year. 
As a result, an increasing number of companies are facing 
bankruptcy, while others have been forced to halt production. 
The ban on transit through Yugoslavia (Serbia/Montenegro) was 
introduced in April 1993, when the U.N. sanctions imposed in 
late May 1992, were tightened. 
  The Greek authorities closed their border and imposed a 
trade 
embargo on the FYROM last January after some E.U. countries 
recognized it as an independent state. Athens strongly opposes 
the FYROM being recognized under the name of Macedonia, 
explaining that this name is closely linked with the Greek 
history and that it indicates FYROM's territorial claims. The 
anti-Yugoslav blockade has so far cost the FYROM three billion 
U.S. dollars. 
  Two million U.S. dollars have been earmarked for the "south 
wing" of the so-called customs corridor, i.e. for the widening 
of two bottlenecks at the border crossings Deve Bair (to 
Bulgaria) and Chafa San (to Albania). That, however, has only 
dimmed the essence of the problem. 
  Shipping agents in the FYROM are aware that the corridor 
through Bulgaria and in particular the one through Albania 
cannot be compared to the routes towards Europe via Serbia. 
  Although the distance between the border crossing Chafa San 
and the Albanian port of Durres is only 148 km, trailer trucks 
need over nine hours to cover that section because it is in a 
very bad condition. Moreover, they are in constant fear from 
road bandits or police "controls." The port of Durres, which 
gained in popularity after the Thessaloniki port was shut down 
to goods from the FYROM last February, is unable to meet all 
requirements. 
  While transport charges in the world amount for 5-12 per 
cent 
in produce costs, the transport of FYROM goods to Europe via 
Albania and Bulgaria hikes up these costs to as much as 50 per 
cent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-31375 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu111_m_94005" </HT>


