<H3> <TI>   Democratic Party Cited on Lack of Democracy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Democratic Party Cited on Lack of Democracy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0806133794 Skopje MILS-NEWS in English 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0806133794 </F>
<F P=104>  Skopje MILS-NEWS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Police Effort To Destroy Opposition"] </F>
  [Text] "The state police is against democracy in Macedonia 
[The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] and is 
using all means possible to stay in power, which is a severe 
blow to basic human rights as this involves methods of 
manipulation with the public and police intervention in the 
spheres of inalienable civil rights." Peter Gosev, leader of 
the Democratic Party said at yesterday's press conference. 
  As arguments for this, Gosev stated frequent and 
long-lasting 
blocking of the work of parliament, not by the opposition, but 
by the ruling party, which refuses to attend sessions or limits 
debates on "inconvenient" subjects. He also spoke of increased 
influence of political parties over the institutions of 
democracy, through unscrupulous party interfering into judicial 
matters, covering up for criminal charges against high state 
officials, and not starting bankruptcy proceedings in certain 
firms. 
  "The highest police officials are leading a politics of 
destroying the opposition." Gosev said. In order to do this, 
according to Gosev, they are increasingly using satellite 
parties and individuals known to have been informants for former 
intelligence services. He also said the interior minister was 
turning into a Stalin-type policeman. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

