<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks Continue in Geneva; Cease-Fire Signed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Talks Continue in Geneva; Cease-Fire Signed </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Butrus-Ghali, Karadzic on Accord </H4>

<F P=102> LD0806172894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1639 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806172894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Geneva, June 8 (TANJUG) -- U.N. Secretary-General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali described as relative success the accord on 
the one-month cessation of military activities in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina signed in Geneva Wednesday. This document 
came as a compromise which at the last moment saved from fiasco 
the conference which the Moslem-Croatian delegation for the 
first four days boycotted and then blackmailed to the end. 
  According to a U.N. spokesperson in Geneva, Butrus-Ghali set 
out that the accord was only the first step towards achieving 
lasting cessation of hostilities and finding a generally 
acceptable political solution in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Head of the Bosnian Serb Republic (R.S.) delegation Radovan 
Karadzic said prior to the official announcement on signing the 
accord that the Serb side has once again demonstrated its sense 
for reaching compromise, but expressed doubt this would set the 
Moslems on course to peace and understanding. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-31380 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu111aa_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-111 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks Continue in Geneva; Cease-Fire Signed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Talks Continue in Geneva; Cease-Fire Signed </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Karadzic: Serbs `Not Treated Equally' </H4>

<F P=102> LD0806175194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1720 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806175194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Geneva, June 8 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Serb Republic 
(R.S.) President Radovan Karadzic said Wednesday that partial 
solutions, such as the signing of ceasefire accord for one 
month, pushed towards war and did not represent a basis for 
peace in Bosnia- herzegovina. He told reporters that the Serb 
side was once again not treated equally. 
  The accord -- signed Wednesday by U.N. special envoy Yasushi 
Akashi and Vice-Presidents of the Moslem-Croatian Federation in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Ejup Ganic and the Bosnian Serb Republic 
(R.S.) Nikola Kolrevic -- envisage the two sides refrain from 
engaging for a period of one month in any military activity 
beginning June 10 at noon local time. 
  The signed document, as set out in Geneva, in no way 
(?completed a platform) with which, under Akashi's proposal, the 
conference opened and according to which an accord was to have 
been signed for four-month ceasefire period, as the basic 
pre-condition in finding a comprehensive political solution to 
the Bosnia crisis. 
  The Serbs have from the outset of the conference requested a 
lasting ceasefire, while the Moslem Croatian delegation first 
boycotted for four days the talks, under the pretext that armed 
Serbs did not leave the three-kilometer exclusion zone around 
Gorazde, a Moslem enclave in eastern Bosnia, as set out in the 
U.N. Resolution No.913. When the Moslem observers and U.N. 
members on the spot confirmed that armed Serbs have left the 
said area, Ganic said he would accept only talks on a four-week 
ceasefire. 
  The signed accord, clearly designed to suit the Moslem side, 
was taken in Geneva as the first step towards a comprehensive 
cessation of hostilities, something, as set out, about which the 
warring parties would continue discussions over the next few 
days. All this, of course, on condition the Moslems indeed 
intended ever to join in earnest talks on peace and adhere to 
the signed documents, including this one signed Wednesday in 
Geneva. 
  The accord envisaged the warring sides carry out an exchange 
of prisoners and release all captured persons on their 
respective territories as well as submit to the Red Cross lists 
of missing persons. This process is to be scrupulously 
supervised [word indistinct]. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-31381 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu111aa_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-111 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks Continue in Geneva; Cease-Fire Signed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Talks Continue in Geneva; Cease-Fire Signed </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Ganic Comments on Cease-Fire Talks </H4>

<F P=102> LD0806223294 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 2000 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0806223294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Following the conclusion of the Geneva negotiations 
today, Ejup Ganic, head of the Bosnia-Herzegovina delegation and 
vice president of the Federation of Bosnia-Herzegovina, made the 
following statement for Bosnia-Herzegovina Radio and TV: 
  [Begin Ganic recording] The delegation acted in accordance 
with the Assembly guidelines. We fought in a diplomatic way for 
the principles laid down by the Assembly. A few days ago, 
Karadzic's troops withdrew from the 3-km zone around Gorazde -- 
these were soldiers, armed civilians, police, all his army in 
various shapes and forms. Having seen that this condition had 
been met, we began talks and a cease-fire agreement was reached 
which rules out any offensive operations for a one-month period. 
  I must say straight away that huge pressure was exerted on 
our delegation for days to sign a four-month cease-fire, or for 
an even longer period. However, we did not agree to free the 
Serbian side from the obligation to negotiate peace, while on 
the other hand we did not agree to sit and wait for winter. 
Huge pressure was exerted on us. We fought with arguments -- 
we only had foreign journalists on our side. 
  Every day we made public statements and we compared the 
situation: Our citizens know that several days ago Europe 
celebrated D-Day, when the allies landed in Normandy to have a 
showdown with Hitler, a showdown with fascism. I said that 
nowadays we, the unarmed Bosnians, are trying to have a showdown 
with a resurrected fascism. I called on the European public to 
unite as they united then against fascism. We cannot do that 
job unarmed. That virus of ethnic cleansing and genocide, which 
the international community has nurtured in Bosnia by ignoring 
the aggression of Serbian fascism, is now spreading throughout 
the world, causing real chaos. 
  In other words, a parallel was drawn between what happened 
during the Normandy landing and the final showdown with fascism, 
and these negotiations here. Many correspondents were in fact 
on our side, interpreting our stands, so an agreement on a 
four-week cease-fire was finally reached, as we proposed in the 
beginning. 
  A new stage in the negotiations -- a new kind of talks 
directed at reducing the military potential in Bosnia -- will be 
formulated soon. This primarily regards the removal of heavy 
weaponry, in the event the embargo on arms sales to Bosnia's 
Muslims is not lifted, then -- if the world believes that too 
many weapons cause too much war -- the formula less weapons, 
less war, should be applied, which means that the Serbian regime 
and its army should be disarmed. We shall be formulating a new 
[word indistinct] for such talks in a couple of days, and this 
has been agreed. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

