<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economic Issues To Be Discussed in Plitvice </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Economic Issues To Be Discussed in Plitvice </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806154994 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1507 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806154994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Knin, June 8 (TANJUG) -- President of the republic 
of Serb Krajina (RSK) Milan Martic has agreed that the first 
round of talks on economic issues with the Croatian side be held 
on June 16-17 in Plitvice in RSK territory, the office of the 
RSK president said in a statement on Wednesday. Martic made the 
decision after receiving additional international guarantees 
that all issues relating to the Croatia-Krajina conflict would 
in future be resolved through talks on an equal footing and that 
the international community would not tolerate Croatia's policy 
of force, the RSK news agency ISKRA reports. 
  Moreover, says ISKRA, Martic also received firm guarantees 
that a political settlement would not be prejudged in any stage 
of the talks and that it should be sought within the 
Geneva-based international conference on the former Yugoslavia. 
Martic's office also said that the RSK president had decided to 
agree to the talks after consultations with co-chairmen of the 
international conference Lord Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg and 
U.N. special envoy Yasushi Akashi. 
  The RSK was founded in late 1991 in the Serb ancestral lands 
in Croatia in response to Croatia's violent secession from the 
former Yugoslav federation and attempts to downgrade the Serbs 
to a national minority. In March 1992, the RSK was placed under 
U.N. protection. 
  Martic's talks with the international mediators in Geneva 
also tackled the implementation of the RSK-Croatia truce signed 
in the Russian Embassy in Zagreb last spring. The RSK president 
said that Croatia had not fully honoured the agreement and 
warned that this could seriuosly impede the peace process. 
  Akashi personally guaranteed that he would insist with the 
Croatian side to immediately meet the obligations it undertook 
under the truce agreement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

