<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnian Serb Official Lists Disputed Areas </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnian Serb Official Lists Disputed Areas </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806162494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1535 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0806162494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Banja Luka, 8 Jun (TANJUG) -- "The remaining 
disputed issues concern western and eastern Herzegovina, Posanje 
(the Sana river valley), the towns of Krupa na Uni, Prijedor, 
Sanski Most, Podrinje, the towns of Gorazde, Visegrad, and the 
wider Srebrenica area -- territories they wish to take away from 
the Serbs." This was stated by Momcilo Krajisnik, president of 
the republic of Srpska's national assembly, in a statement for 
today's edition of GLAS SRPSKI of Banja Luka. He said that the 
republic of Srpska delegation pointed to the shortcomings of 
their demand to cede 51 percent of the former Bosnia-Herzegovina 
to the Muslim-Croat federation if the quality and quantity of 
the territory is not taken into account. 
  "We explained that the tendency to expand Muslim and 
Croatian 
territories at the expense of the Serbs is unacceptable and in 
poor taste," Krajisnik said, adding that the Serbs cannot 
possibly renounce lands that represent a vital interest of the 
Serbian nation, as is the case with Posavina. 
  "They envisage only a narrow corridor for the republic of 
Srpska, although this territory is the only link the western 
Serb lands have with Serbia proper," Krajisnik said in his 
statement for "GLAS SRPSKI." "In any case, this territory is of 
much greater importance to the Serbs than it could be to the 
Croats or Muslims." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

